export interface SectionHtml { anchor: string; html: string }

export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "s8-1", "html": "<p>Ammonia synthesis is the largest catalytic energy sink on Earth: roughly 2% of world energy consumption and ~1.4% of global CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span> emissions across ~176–180 Mt/yr of production.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"36\">[36]</sup> Green hydrogen is the second anchor, bottlenecked by metals: the primary literature asks in its title whether iridium demand is &quot;a potential bottleneck in the realization of large-scale PEM water electrolysis,&quot; while US Department of Energy targets call for PEM capital cost to fall from ~$1,500/kW (2020) to under $150/kW by 2030.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"55\">[55]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"222\">[222]</sup> And demand policy has arrived: in June 2026 China committed to 2 Mt/yr of renewable hydrogen by 2030, on a reported installed base already past 220 kt/yr — over half the global total.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"56\">[56]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"35\">[35]</sup></p>\n<p>Chapter 7's barrier blindness extends from ion migration to surface reaction; catalysis adds a second failure mode batteries mostly lack — the surface itself moves. Both sit on the inherited label floor argued throughout this paper, and in catalysis that floor has been measured twice against experiment, then documented as a plateau by the dataset's own builders. The thesis here is narrow: the ±0.2 eV adsorption floor is inherited, not trained away, and the class's own 2024–2025 meta-analyses now say so.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s8-2-1", "html": "<p>The canonical benchmark is Wellendorff et al.'s 2015 database of 39 experimental adsorption energies on single-crystal transition-metal facets, themselves accurate to 0.02–0.1 eV: against it, GGA functionals (PBE, RPBE, BEEF-vdW-class) show mean errors of 0.2–0.4 eV (0.2 eV ≈ 4.6 kcal/mol ≈ 19.3 kJ/mol; 96.485 kJ/mol = 1 eV).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"12\">[12]</sup> Climbing Jacob's ladder does not rescue this: the random-phase approximation, the best tractable many-body method, &quot;predicts adsorption energies that deviate by 0.2 eV from experiments,&quot; and per reaction RPA and DFT disagree by up to 0.5 eV.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"73\">[73]</sup> A 2024 functional assessment for the nitrogen adsorbates of ammonia and NO<span class=\"math\">$_x$</span> chemistry reproduces the same ~0.2 eV spread.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"223\">[223]</sup> I read this pair of benchmarks as the paper's strongest evidence for the inherited-floor thesis: when the two best reference methods affordable at screening scale each sit ~0.2 eV from experiment and disagree with each other by up to 0.5 eV per reaction, the label noise is structural, and every ML model trained on it inherits the offset before any model error is added.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s8-2-2", "html": "<p>Open Catalyst 2020 — 1{,}281{,}040 DFT relaxations (~264,890,000 single-point evaluations), every label generated by one functional flavor (RPBE) — is the flagship corpus.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"224\">[224]</sup> Its builders document the plateau themselves: &quot;the energy MAE of the models appears to plateau at ~0.2 eV for the past two years,&quot; against a &quot;target accuracy [of] 0.1 eV which is the estimated error level of the DFT calculations.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup> For this class the reading is direct: the plateau sits exactly at label accuracy, so the adsorption-energy error a catalyst screen carries is inherited from the labels, not trained away (Chapter 3 derives the floor; the −35% reconstruction-referencing correction is a single-study figure).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s8-2-3", "html": "<p>Transition states are worse. On a 2025 CO-oxidation benchmark on PdAg, universal MLIPs reproduce DFT-NEB barriers with mean absolute errors (MAEs) of 0.10–0.15 eV, plus outright transition-state-search failures.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"225\">[225]</sup> MS25 makes the point at meV energy accuracy: models posting ~0.2 meV/atom energy errors reproduce its 0.74 eV CH<span class=\"math\">$_4$</span>-on-Pt barrier only within ±0.06 eV.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> The amplification is arithmetic: 0.06 eV (≈1 kcal/mol) of barrier error is a factor of ten in rate at 300 K (the <span class=\"math\">$e^{\\varepsilon/k_BT}$</span> conversion is derived in Chapter 3). The class's canonical uncertainty study concluded that only relative rates between catalysts, and the probability of beating a known standard, survive DFT-level error bars.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"226\">[226]</sup> A December 2025 meta-analysis then quantified the screening consequence: ~0.3–0.5 eV is a <em>conservative</em> uncertainty for one DFT adsorption energy, and overpotential ranking &quot;misclassif[ies] a broad fraction of the datasets as 'good'&quot; — its reported quantification, up to ~47% of OER and ~37% of HER candidates falling inside the best-in-class window, is a single-study figure I treat as indicative, not settled.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"44\">[44]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s8-2-4", "html": "<p>Some failures are categorical, not parametric. In the two-decade CO/Pt(111) puzzle, semilocal DFT places CO in the fcc hollow, 0.109 eV below the top site, while experiment — and hybrid HSE06 (−0.086 eV) — put it on top.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"74\">[74]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"227\">[227]</sup> No error bar rescues a screen that ranks the wrong site first; the mechanism built on that site is wrong from step one. The ML-functional fix is real but bounded: DeePKS resolves the puzzle at PBE cost in-domain, yet transferring the Cu-trained model to Rh(111) yields &quot;fatal failures in adsorption energies … with errors exceeding 1 eV/atom.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"227\">[227]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s8-2-5", "html": "<p>Under CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>-reduction bias, Cu surfaces restructure into in-situ-formed metallic nanograins that act as the active phase (Nature, 2023).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"228\">[228]</sup> Cu single-atom catalysts &quot;are converted into 2-nm Cu nanoparticles&quot; during CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>RR, and single-site catalysts generally &quot;transform in situ to metallic agglomerations under working conditions.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"229\">[229]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"230\">[230]</sup> The corpora encode static, idealized slabs; the reconstruction that leaks into the labels corrupts referencing (§8.2.2) rather than teaching physics.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup> A screen ranking static structures is therefore, in part, ranking catalysts that cease to exist at operating potential.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 8.1 — The catalysis error stack, layer by layer (figures verified as of 2026-07-17; MAE = mean absolute error).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Layer</th>\n<th>Verified figure</th>\n<th>Consequence</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>GGA adsorption energies vs experiment</td>\n<td>Mean errors 0.2–0.4 eV; experiment itself good to 0.02–0.1 eV <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"12\">[12]</sup></td>\n<td>Every activity descriptor downstream inherits the offset</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>RPA (best tractable many-body)</td>\n<td>~0.2 eV mean deviation from experiment; per-reaction RPA-vs-DFT gaps to 0.5 eV <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"73\">[73]</sup></td>\n<td>&quot;Buy a better functional&quot; fails at screening cost</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>OC20 ML energy MAE (vs RPBE labels)</td>\n<td>~0.2 eV plateau for ~2 years vs 0.1 eV target <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup></td>\n<td>Screening ranks stall at the label floor</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>uMLIP NEB barriers vs DFT</td>\n<td>MAE 0.10–0.15 eV plus TS-search failures <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"225\">[225]</sup>; MS25: 0.74 eV CH<span class=\"math\">$_4$</span>/Pt barrier ±0.06 eV at ~0.2 meV/atom energy error <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup></td>\n<td>0.06 eV ≈ 10<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> rate at 300 K; ranks order-of-magnitude noisy</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CO/Pt(111) site preference</td>\n<td>Semilocal DFT favors fcc hollow by +0.109 eV; experiment and HSE06 favor top site (−0.086 eV) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"227\">[227]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"74\">[74]</sup></td>\n<td>Mechanism-level misidentification, invisible to MAE</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Read top to bottom, the table's structure is the argument. The first two rows are reference-method floors measured against experiment, not against another simulation. The third row is the ML layer asymptoting at its labels' accuracy — Chapter 3's two-layer inheritance model in one dataset. The fourth row is where money is lost: rates, not energies, decide viability, and Arrhenius amplification turns a respectable 0.1 eV barrier MAE into order-of-magnitude rank noise before DFT-versus-experiment error is added. The fifth row is the floor beneath the floor: an error no ensemble spread flags, because the functional is confidently wrong about which site is active. A correction program that fixes only row three leaves the other four intact.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s8-3", "html": "<p>Chapter 3's scoreboard binds catalysis on Row 10 (the reference-functional ceiling) and Row 6 (the benchmark–reality gap), with Row 1's non-equilibrium data as partial relief. The demonstrated fidelity lever is Row 3's Δ-learning: one study finds a model trained on 90% GGA plus 10% SCAN matching one trained on 8<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> as much SCAN data — hybrid-accuracy screening at near-GGA label cost.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"20\">[20]</sup> DeePKS proves an ML correction can carry GGA energetics to hybrid fidelity,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"227\">[227]</sup> and ML-plus-RPA coverage curves extend the escalation to coverage dependence — the second systematic gap between slab models and operating surfaces.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"20\">[20]</sup> OCx24 is the validation template: 572 synthesized samples, 441 gas-diffusion electrodes tested at up to 300 mA/cm², and DFT-verified adsorption energies on ~20,000 materials from 685 million AI-accelerated relaxations — built to close &quot;the gap between what AI-accelerated computational models predict and what experimental studies produce.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"231\">[231]</sup> The spin-aware, experiment-coupled AQCat25 dataset extends the same direction.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"232\">[232]</sup> Gap and target are both quantified: today, ~0.2 eV adsorption error versus experiment and 0.10–0.15 eV barrier MAE; solved, adsorption within ~0.1 eV of experiment at screening scale and barrier MAE ≤40 meV (Row 7's target). My working bet, per the §3.7 replication sequence: 90:10 Δ-learning onto hybrid labels plus non-equilibrium augmentation and operando-anchored validation is the cheapest demonstrated path between those columns, and every component is published — none needs a new foundation model.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s8-4", "html": "<p>The strongest skepticism in this class comes from inside it — the OC20 team's own plateau analysis above,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup> and the December 2025 Chatterjee et al. meta-analysis, which &quot;calls for a shift in focus in the computational catalysis and machine learning communities towards other metrics such as synthesizability, stability, lifetime or affordability.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"44\">[44]</sup> The NeurIPS 2025 MLIP Arena states that &quot;existing benchmarks suffer from data leakage, limited transferability, and an over-reliance on error-based metrics tied to specific DFT references.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"229\">[229]</sup> The record matches: no ML-predicted heterogeneous catalyst has been commercialized as of 2026-07-17 — an absence-of-evidence claim, but one for which I found no counterexample. The flagship claim that did survive experiment, Cu–Al for CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>-to-ethylene (Nature 2020), delivered a real but incremental gain — ~60% versus ~35% Faradaic efficiency at 600 mA/cm² — and no commercial catalyst.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"233\">[233]</sup> The DFT-guided nitrogen-reduction literature collapsed outright under quantitative isotope protocols (Nature 2019), and ARPA-E's own electrochemical-ammonia performance targets remain unmet.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"234\">[234]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"35\">[35]</sup> The honest gains are throughput, not discovery: AdsorbML recovers the correct lowest-energy configuration 87.36% of the time at a 2,000<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> speed-up — so one hit in eight is misranked even <em>within</em> DFT accuracy, before Table 8.1's other rows apply.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"235\">[235]</sup> I take the counter-narrative at full strength: ML currently accelerates known-physics screening, and the burden of proof for anything beyond that sits with the discovery claims, not with the skeptics.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s8-5", "html": "<p>Beijing has made electrolyzer-relevant hydrogen demand a national target: the NDRC/NEA new-energy-system plan for the 15th Five-Year Plan period (2026-06-25) sets renewable hydrogen production of 2 Mt/yr by 2030.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"236\">[236]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"56\">[56]</sup> Washington's arc is turbulent, stated plainly: the Hydrogen Shot (&quot;$1 for 1 kg in 1 decade&quot;) launched in 2021;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"222\">[222]</sup> in October 2025 DOE terminated $2.2 billion for the ARCHES and Pacific Northwest electrolytic hubs inside a $7.5 billion rollback;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"237\">[237]</sup> on 2026-01-12 a federal judge ruled those cancellations illegal, with funding not automatically restored and appeals pending;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"238\">[238]</sup> the Earthshots initiative page persists as dormant legacy content.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"239\">[239]</sup> The neutral reading: the demand driver for cheap-electrolyzer catalysts currently sits on the Beijing side, and US program uncertainty raises the premium on validated, buyer-agnostic candidates a program office or industrial buyer can pick up without a policy forecast.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s8-6", "html": "<p>This chapter feeds the roadmap's third chain: Δ-learned hybrid-accuracy screening plus operando validation → Ir-free electrolyzer and ammonia catalysts → sub-$2/kg green hydrogen, decarbonized fertilizer and steel. I promise no dates; the honest statement is that each component fix is demonstrated and the composite is within reach of demonstration. What I sell is narrower and, I argue, more valuable: validated candidates, not overpotential leaderboards. The procurement template already exists in the adjacent porous-frameworks class — which is why I import it here.</p>\n<div class=\"pullbox\">\n<p><strong>Case box 8.1 — The procurement-grade funnel: Kemira–CuspAI (2026).</strong>\nKemira defined the brief: materials to remove specific PFAS molecules from drinking water at sub-parts-per-billion concentrations, using chemistry that is &quot;water-stable, environmentally compatible, synthesizable, and cost-effective.&quot; CuspAI designed metal–organic frameworks from scratch across ~300 trillion possible structures, delivered over 5,000 novel designs with property data on all three target molecules, and narrowed them to ~20 priority candidates — in six months. The project has moved into development and testing, with further programs scoped under a framework agreement.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"240\">[240]</sup>\nThree features make this the model of what buyers purchase. The buyer owns the brief and the qualification pipeline. The binding constraints are synthesizability-and-stability class, not activity class — the exact pivot Chatterjee et al. prescribe.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"44\">[44]</sup> The deliverable is a small, property-annotated candidate set on a deadline: six months from 300 trillion structures to ~20 candidates is a funnel a customer can price — a leaderboard rank is not.</p>\n</div>\n<p>Chapter 14 develops the stability-first doctrine in full; the catalyst-specific implication is already visible. A funnel that identifies makeable, operando-stable candidates converts the same ±0.2 eV accuracy into validated outcomes; an activity-only funnel converts it into misclassified best-in-class windows. The class does not need another leaderboard; it needs its first procurement-grade catalyst funnel, and the components to build one are published, priced, and waiting.</p>\n" },
]
